						<summary>

						<p>Slab in the compound of the Goṭēśvara temple.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Tribhuvanamalla [Vikramāditya VI] 1122 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>This damaged record contains a genealogical account of the Chālukya family and refers to the reign of Chālukya Tribhuvanamalla who is stated to have been ruling from the capital Jayantipura. It registers a grant of land and a garden for the worship of god Iśvara by <hi rend="italic">manneya</hi> Bibbarasa and the <hi rend="italic">prajes.</hi> Sōmēśvarajīya, the priest of the temple was also given 20 <hi rend="italic">mattar</hi> land by the donors.</p>						

						<p>The record is dated in Chālukya Vikrama year 46, Plava, Phālguṇa, amāvāsya, Friday, solar eclipse. It corresponds to 1122 A.D., March 10, Friday. Solar eclipse occured on that day.</p>						

						</summary>
